			<span class="hed1"><a name="spot"></a>IN THE SPOTLIGHT<br><br> 
           Vanuatu's Kava Culture</span> 
			
			<p class="text">
			If you're visiting Vanuatu (a South Pacific island nation) you may find the nightlife a little lacklustre, that is, until you discover kava... Lonely Planet author Michelle Bennett investigates:
			</p>
			
<p class="text">Variously known as sakau, yaqona or `ava throughout the Pacific, kava is the drink of choice in Vanuatu. Many people wouldn't consider a day complete without throwing back a couple of 'shells' of the stuff. Traditionally and more formally though, a kava ceremony is held to welcome visitors, seal alliances, start chiefly conferences and to commemorate births, deaths and marriages.</p>
              <p class="text">For such special occasions, there are strict rules 
                for preparing and drinking kava, and preparation procedures vary 
                throughout Vanuatu's 83 islands. On parts of Tanna, for example, 
                kava roots are brought to the nakamal (men's clubhouse) each afternoon 
                by pre-pubescent boys. The boys prepare the roots by chewing them 
                into a mush, which is then mixed with water and filtered through 
                coconut fibres. (Don't let the chewing bit turn you off - in many 
                places these days the roots are simply ground up, no spit involved...)</p>
<p class="text">This liquid mixture is then poured into a half-coconut shell, which serves as a cup (hence, the term 'shell' for a draught of kava). First the chief drinks it, followed by any honoured guests, then other men drink in order of precedence. Etiquette requires drinking each shell in a single gulp; any remaining liquid is poured on the ground. It's also generally drunk in a quiet atmosphere: conversation and loud noises are kept to a minimum.</p>
<p class="text">While many people visiting Vanuatu won't have the honour of witnessing or participating in a traditional kava ceremony, the fact that it's also consumed regularly as a social drink means that the opportunity to try some is never too far away.</p>
<p class="text">You'll find that kava has a pungent, muddy and slightly peppery taste - it looks like very dirty dishwater, and many would say it doesn't taste much better. But it's not that bad, in fact given a chance it definitely grows on you. If the brew is a strong one - and there's a good chance it will be as Vanuatu's kava is reputedly the strongest in the world - your lips will go numb and cold almost instantly (even my throat went numb!). Then after about 20 minutes your limbs will feel heavy, your speech will become quiet and slow and your eyes will be sensitive to any glare (kava bars are very dimly lit because of this). Even if it's only a mild brew, you'll probably want to do nothing more than lie down and think about life, feeling sedated and happy.</p>
<p class="text">On many of the more remote, tradition-oriented islands of Vanuatu, kava drinking is an exclusively male activity surrounded by all sorts of tabu (taboos). However, in other areas, especially in the capital Port Vila, where there are over 100 kava bars, most being little more than iron sheds, women are generally more than welcome to join in.</p>
              <p class="text">In addition to its ceremonial and social uses, some 
                of the 40 sub-species of kava (known botanically as Piper methysticum), 
                are used locally as bush medicine, as they contain natural pain 
                and appetite-suppressants as well as antibacterial, relaxant, 
                diuretic and decongestant properties. Over the past decade, kava-based 
                food supplements and herbal medicines also gained popularity in 
                Europe, Australia and the USA for alleviating stress, anxiety 
                and insomnia. For a while there it was an increasingly lucrative 
                export market for Vanuatu, and its Pacific pals Fiji, Samoa and 
                Tonga.</p>
<p class="text">In November 2001, however, the latest 'wonder drug' received bad press when the European Union announced that consumption of kava could be linked to liver damage. So far, the evidence is inconclusive. It may be that kava manufactured into capsules is the problem, rather than kava drunk as a liquid (the active ingredient in kava, kavalactone, is much more concentrated in pill form). Your average Ni-Vanuatu may be testament to this theory: they certainly don't look any the worse for wear, even those who have drunk the stuff daily for years. For visitors to the Pacific who haven't been imbibing kava for centuries though, it may be a case of everything in moderation.</p>

