                Ticker: <a href="http://www.lonelyplanet.com/travel_ticker" target="_blank">www.lonelyplanet.com/travel_ticker</a> 
              </p>            
			  <p class="text">Brand spanking new titles on the bookshelves this 
                season include Morocco, Europe, Spain, Turkey and our first US 
                National Park guide to Yosemite. For a full list of LP titles 
                and a sneak peek at what's about to roll off the press visit: 
                <a href="http://shop.lonelyplanet.com" target="_blank">http://shop.lonelyplanet.com</a></p>
			  <p class="text">Have you noticed a new web page on the ekno website 
                after logging in? We have added a new information web page that 
                highlights product updates, special offers and hints and tips 
                about the service to help you get the most out of ekno on your 
                next trip. Visit the website and see for yourself: <a href="http://www.ekno.lonelyplanet.com" target="_blank">www.ekno.lonelyplanet.com</a></p> 
			
			
<table width="100%"><tr>
                  <td align="right"><a href="#top"><img src="http://www.lonelyplanet.com/comet/nl_graffix/top.gif" alt="top" border="0"></a></td>
                </tr></table>
<hr>
<br>	

			<span class="hed1"><a name="five"></a>TOP 5<br><br> 
</span> 			
			<p class="text">This issue of Comet was put together as Muslims filled-up the empty spaces left by the Ramadan fast, as Jews finished the last of the Hannukah treats, and as Christians began the run-up to Christmas feasting. Entering the spirit of monotheistic surfeit, Comet is rewarding not one, not two but three readers for their Top 5s this month! And there's even a stocking-stuffer of two very useful travel tips at the end. (We realise that those festivals are now just distant memories, but we'll buck the trend of selling Eatser Eggs in January, and look back rather than forward. Comet makes its own rules!)</p> 
			  <p class="text"><b>From Mike Post</b></p> 
			<p class="text">On endless journeys by bus/train/boat/plane, or when being imprisoned in solitary confinement and your mind's too pulpy to read or talk, take your time and try to remember the following:</p>
			<p class="text">
1. year and circumstances of your first kiss<br>

2. year and circumstances of your first booze<br>

3. year and circumstances of your first journey<br>

4. year and circumstances of your first love; then<br>

5. list all next-times of the above.<br></p>

			  <p class="text"><b>From Nikki Hudson</b></p> 
			<p class="text">There is nothing more useful when backpacking than the basic essentials; penknife, torch etc, but I always carry a plastic mug - why, you ask? Well below are my top 5 reasons why but there are stacks of uses for this small and multipurpose piece of equipment.</p>

<p class="text">1. The obvious - drink out of it - easier than drinking with your hands or out of the bottle.</p> 

<p class="text">2. Clean your teeth in it - not literally - but using a small amount of water to wash your brush in. Whilst travelling you always feel 100% better with sparklingly clean teeth. It also saves water, since you're not tipping this precious commodity over your brush and feet.</p> 

<p class="text">3. Put your watch, lipsalve, penknife, small torch etc in it when you go to sleep - this way they're really easy to find in the morning and you're not messing about searching under your sleeping bag.</p> 

<p class="text">4. You can use it to trap creepy crawlies under when they have ventured into your tent, or trap and transport back outside those sneaky earwigs.</p> 

<p class="text">5. Transport home those little breakable items that you inevitably collect. It's solid and so with the fragiles packed in and stood upright in the side pocket of your backpack they're sure to get home in one piece. For added security you could put the mug in a sock and surround the whole thing with more socks!</p> 
			

			  <p class="text"><b>From Vicki M</b></p> 
			<p class="text">Top 5 ways to get a leave of absence from work in order to travel.</p>

<p class="text">1. Show the boss how much money will be saved by not paying you while you're away.</p> 

<p class="text">2. Point out that all the other people in your department have taken 
maternity leave (one year in Canada), while you're only asking for a measly 
few months....
</p> 

<p class="text">3. Catch your boss in an appropriate mood, ie, when they're wistfully 
thinking about tacking a vacation on to that conference they're attending 
next year.
</p> 

<p class="text">4. Do ALL the mountains of paperwork yourself so in the end, all they have 
to do is sign on the dotted line.
</p> 

<p class="text">5.  Promise to never never never tell anyone else you work with what you're 
doing so that they won't ask for the same thing...

</p> 
<p class="text">...all of which I have done this year to get my time off! Vicki M.</p>			

 <p class="text"><b>From Todd Lang</b></p> 
			<p class="text">There is no better way to use dryer lint than to use it as a fire starter when camping. It's cheap, light, and lights easily with a match. Maybe other readers have better ways to use dryer lint, but this is the only one I have. I could not even come up with a top five for it!</p>
			
<p class="text"><b>From Janet Domas</b></p> 
			<p class="text">My travel hot tip is DENTAL FLOSS</p>
						
<p class="text">It's light-weight, durable and you wouldn't leave home without it. I first discovered its versatility when I purchased a black pearl pendant in Bora Bora. I was anxious to wear my new beauty but had not packed a necklace, so I strung it on dental floss and wore it proudly.</p>
<p class="text">I have also used it as an early alert system by tying a chair to a door knob after seeing suspicious characters wander the halls of the place I was staying.</p>
<p class="text">It works for hanging a flashlight in your tent, and in a pinch as a shoelace.</p>

