<br>	

			<span class="hed1"><a name="post"></a>POSTCARDS<br><br> 

<p class="text"><b>From Tamsin Ranger, travel addict</b> (affectionately referred to on the road as Lone Ranger)</p>

<p class="text">When I was new to the travelling world, I experienced many a safety wake-up call whilst travelling carefree (or should I say carelessly?) through Thailand. An incident I still remember with rosy cheeks is my quest for a brand-name track top. Whilst scouting Khao San Road, I came across a rack of fake adidas clothing, unable to find what I wanted the stall owner promised to return the following day.</p>
<p class="text">The next morning I found the stall owner, but he could not bring his wares down Khao San in his truck as the road was too busy, he did however offer to take us to his store 'room'. I gladly followed, determined to get my label wear. We followed the small Thai man down a dirty, narrow and 'pungent' alley and turned into a door. The door we were entering was in fact a dark, seedy looking pool bar called "the hole in the wall" (how fitting). We were lead through the bar, where several large men regarded us suspiciously, and onto to a rickety spiral staircase.</p>
<p class="text">At this point reality kicked in, in the form of my travel companion. She tugged my sleeve and mentioned that perhaps going up a winding staircase into who knows what with a scary looking Thai man might not be the wisest thing we could do. I asked the man if he could bring the wares downstairs but he insisted we had to go up with him. Reluctantly we followed, shoving our passports into our knickers, convinced we were about to re-enact a scene from Brokedown Palace, and that this would be a story parents warned their travelling children about.</p>
<p class="text">Upon reaching the top of the stairs, our guide opened a door into a small room. There were three mattresses strewn across the floor and three Thai men stood around drinking coffee and regarding us lasciviously. I knew then and there that we were about to be sold to the white sex trade and would never again see the light of day.Then and there, our guide invited us in and showed us the racks of fake clothing stored in the corner and his friends promptly offered us cups of tea and a free Farang magazine. Visions of leaving intact and safe (with my track top) flooded my brain and after a chat with the surprisingly friendly gentlemen we left unscathed, although rather shaken.</p>
<p class="text">Tip: No need to be paranoid, but before following a seemingly friendly Thai man down alleys (or in fact anywhere) ask yourself whether the situation has the potential to turn into an urban legend to be discussed on the Thorn Tree!!</p>

